statement.p:
Here is an example. The vertices are points and the edges are lines connecting pairs of points.




\begin{tikzpicture} %mathbook width=30%

\tikzstyle{every node}=[draw,circle,fill=black,minimum size=4pt,
inner sep=0pt]

\node (X1) at (0,0) [label=below left:u] {};
\node (X2) at (2,0)  [label=below:v] {};
\node (X3) at (2.5,1.5)  [label=above right:w] {};
\node (X4) at (1,3) [label=above:x] {};
\node (X5) at (1,1)  [label=below left:y] {};
\node (X6) at (0,2)  [label=above right:z] {};

\draw[thick] (X1) -- (X2) -- (X3) -- (X1);

\draw[thick] (X2) -- (X4) -- (X5) -- (X6);

\draw[thick] (X6) -- (X1);

\draw[thick] (X5) -- (X3);



\end{tikzpicture}






This graph G has |V|=6 and |E|=9.







 (u,v) is an edge that is incident with both u and v. Therefore, u and v are adjacent.






 (x,w) is  not an edge






 w is incident with 3 edges, so its degree is \deg(w)=3.















 What are the degrees of  the vertices of G?








 The graph G is drawn so that some of the edges are crossing, meaning that they intersect. For example, edge e_1 = (x,v) crosses edge e_2 = (y,w). Create another drawing of the graph G so that none of the edges are crossing.










 The complement \overline{G} of graph G is the "graph of edges missing in G."  It has the same vertices as G. But the edge (u,v) \in E(\overline{G}) if and only if (u,v) \notin V(G). Draw the complement
\overline{G} of the graph G.  Can you draw \overline{G} so that none of its edges are crossing?

li.p:
 Paths. The path P_n is the graph consisting of a path on n vertices.




\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=.5] %mathbook width=80%





\begin{scope}[shift={(0,-1)}]


\draw[thick] (0,0) -- (1,0);
\draw[fill] (0,0) circle (3pt);
\draw[fill] (1,0) circle (3pt);


\node at (-.5, 0) {\smallP_2};

\end{scope}



\begin{scope}[shift={(0,0)}]

\foreach \x in {0,...,1}
{
{
\draw[thick] (\x,0) -- (\x+1,0);
\draw[fill] (\x,0) circle (3pt);
}

\draw[fill] (2, 0) circle (3pt);
}

\node at (-.5, 0) {\smallP_3};


\end{scope}



\begin{scope}[shift={(4,0)}]

\foreach \x in {0,...,2}
{
{
\draw[thick] (\x,0) -- (\x+1,0);
\draw[fill] (\x,0) circle (3pt);
}

\draw[fill] (3, 0) circle (3pt);
}

\node at (3.5, 0) {\smallP_4};

\end{scope}


\begin{scope}[shift={(3,-1)}]

\foreach \x in {0,...,3}
{
{
\draw[thick] (\x,0) -- (\x+1,0);
\draw[fill] (\x,0) circle (3pt);
}

\draw[fill] (4, 0) circle (3pt);
}

\node at (4.5, 0) {\smallP_5};

\end{scope}


\end{tikzpicture}







How many edges are there in P_n for n \geq 2?

 Cycles. The cycle C_n is the graph corresponding to a closed walk on n vertices whose only repetition is the first/last vertex.




\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=.75] %mathbook width=80%




\begin{scope}[shift={(0,0)}]

\foreach \x in {0,...,2}
{
{
\draw[thick] (120*\x  :1) -- (120*\x+120 :1);
}

\draw[fill] (120*\x: 1) circle (3pt);
}

\node at (0, -1.5) {\smallC_3};


\end{scope}

\begin{scope}[shift={(3,0)}]

\foreach \x in {0,...,3}
{
{
\draw[thick] (90*\x  :1) -- (90*\x + 90 :1);
}

\draw[fill] (90*\x: 1) circle (3pt);
}

\node at (0, -1.5) {\smallC_4};


\end{scope}


\begin{scope}[shift={(6,0)}]

\foreach \x in {0,...,4}
{
{
\draw[thick] (72*\x  :1) -- (72*\x + 72 :1);
}

\draw[fill] (72*\x: 1) circle (3pt);
}

\node at (0, -1.5) {\smallC_5};


\end{scope}


\begin{scope}[shift={(9,0)}]

\foreach \x in {0,...,5}
{
{
\draw[thick] (60*\x  :1) -- (60*\x + 60 :1);
}

\draw[fill] (60*\x: 1) circle (3pt);
}

\node at (0, -1.5) {\smallC_6};


\end{scope}





\end{tikzpicture}







How many edges are there is the cycle C_n for n \geq 3?

 Wheels. The wheel W_n is the graph consisting of a cycle C_{n-1} along with a single hub node that is adjacent with each node in that cycle.






\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=.75] %mathbook width=80%




\begin{scope}[shift={(-3,0)}]

\foreach \x in {0,...,2}
{
{
\draw[thick] (120*\x  :1) -- (120*\x + 120 :1);
\draw[thick] (0,0) -- (120*\x  :1);
}

\draw[fill] (120*\x: 1) circle (3pt);
}

\draw[fill] (0,0) circle (3pt);


\node at (0, -1.5) {\smallW_4};


\end{scope}


\begin{scope}[shift={(0,0)}]

\foreach \x in {0,...,3}
{
{
\draw[thick] (90*\x  :1) -- (90*\x + 90 :1);
\draw[thick] (0,0) -- (90*\x  :1);
}

\draw[fill] (90*\x: 1) circle (3pt);
}

\draw[fill] (0,0) circle (3pt);


\node at (0, -1.5) {\smallW_5};


\end{scope}


\begin{scope}[shift={(3,0)}]

\foreach \x in {0,...,4}
{
{
\draw[thick] (72*\x  :1) -- (72*\x + 72 :1);
\draw[thick] (0,0) -- (72*\x  :1);
}

\draw[fill] (72*\x: 1) circle (3pt);
}

\draw[fill] (0,0) circle (3pt);
\node at (0, -1.5) {\smallW_6};


\end{scope}


\begin{scope}[shift={(6,0)}]

\foreach \x in {0,...,5}
{
{
\draw[thick] (60*\x  :1) -- (60*\x + 60 :1);
\draw[thick] (0,0) -- (60*\x  :1);
}

\draw[fill] (60*\x: 1) circle (3pt);
}

\draw[fill] (0,0) circle (3pt);
\node at (0, -1.5) {\smallW_7};


\end{scope}





\end{tikzpicture}






How many edges are there in the wheel W_n for n \geq 4?

 Complete Graphs. The complete graph K_n is the graph on n vertices with every possible edge.









\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=.75] %mathbook width=80%


\begin{scope}

\foreach \x in {0,...,1}
{
\foreach \y in {0, ..., \x}
{
\draw[thick] (180*\x  :1) -- (180*\y :1);
}

\draw[fill] (180*\x: 1) circle (3pt);
}

\node at (0, -1.5) {\smallK_2};


\end{scope}

\begin{scope}[shift={(3,0)}]

\foreach \x in {0,...,2}
{
\foreach \y in {0, ..., \x}
{
\draw[thick] (120*\x  :1) -- (120*\y :1);
}

\draw[fill] (120*\x: 1) circle (3pt);
}

\node at (0, -1.5) {\smallK_3};


\end{scope}

\begin{scope}[shift={(6,0)}]

\foreach \x in {0,...,3}
{
\foreach \y in {0, ..., \x}
{
\draw[thick] (90*\x  :1) -- (90*\y :1);
}

\draw[fill] (90*\x: 1) circle (3pt);
}

\node at (0, -1.5) {\smallK_4};


\end{scope}


\begin{scope}[shift={(9,0)}]

\foreach \x in {0,...,4}
{
\foreach \y in {0, ..., \x}
