\draw[thick] (72*\x  :1) -- (72*\y :1);
}

\draw[fill] (72*\x: 1) circle (3pt);
}

\node at (0, -1.5) {\smallK_5};


\end{scope}




\end{tikzpicture}






How many edges are there in the complete graph K_n for n \geq 2?

 Complete Bipartite Graphs. The complete bipartite graph K_{r,s} is the graph whose vertices are divided into sets A and B, where |A|=r and |B|=s. Every vertex in A is adjacent to every vertex in B. There are no other edges.





\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=.75] %mathbook width=50%


\begin{scope}

\foreach \x in {0,1,2}
{
\draw[fill] (0,\x) circle (3pt);

\foreach \y in {.5,1.5}
{
\draw[thick] (0, \x) -- (2,\y);
\draw[fill] (2, \y) circle (3pt);
}


}

\node at (1, -1) {\smallK_{3,2}};


\end{scope}


\begin{scope}[shift={(4,0)}]

\foreach \x in {.5,1.5}
{
\draw[fill] (0,\x) circle (3pt);

\foreach \y in {-1,0,1,2,3}
{
\draw[thick] (0, \x) -- (2,\y);
\draw[fill] (2, \y) circle (3pt);
}


}

\node at (1, -1) {\smallK_{2,5}};


\end{scope}

\end{tikzpicture}




How many edges are there in the complete bipartite graph K_{r,s} for r \geq 1 and s \geq 1?

statement.p:
A graph is connected when every pair of vertices are connected by a path in the graph. Any graph is made up of connected components. In other words, we can view any graph as the union of its components, which are themselves connected graphs.
Below, we see an example of a connected graph and example of a graph with three components.



\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.25]  %mathbook width=80%


\begin{scope}[shift={(0,0)}]

\draw[thick] (0,0) -- (1,0) -- (1,1) -- (0,1) -- (0,0);
\draw[thick] (0,1) -- (1,0);
\draw[thick] (1,1) -- (1.5,1.5);
\draw[thick] (1.5,1.5) -- (2.25,2) -- (2.25, 1) -- (1.5,1.5);


\draw[thick, fill] (0,0) circle (3pt);
\draw[thick,fill] (1,0) circle (3pt);
\draw[thick,fill] (0,1) circle (3pt);
\draw[thick,fill] (1,1) circle (3pt);
\draw[thick,fill] (1.5,1.5) circle (3pt);
\draw[thick,fill] (2.25,2) circle (3pt);
\draw[thick,fill] (2.25,1) circle (3pt);

\node at (1,-1) {connected};


\end{scope}


\begin{scope}[shift={(6,0)}]

\draw[thick]  (1,0) -- (1,1);
\draw[thick] (0,0) -- (0,1);

\draw[thick] (1.5,1.5) -- (2.25,2) -- (2.25, 1) -- (1.5,1.5);


\draw[thick, fill] (0,0) circle (3pt);
\draw[thick,fill] (1,0) circle (3pt);
\draw[thick,fill] (0,1) circle (3pt);
\draw[thick,fill] (1,1) circle (3pt);
\draw[thick,fill] (1.5,1.5) circle (3pt);
\draw[thick,fill] (2.25,2) circle (3pt);
\draw[thick,fill] (2.25,1) circle (3pt);

\node at (1,-1) {disconnected};

\end{scope}

\end{tikzpicture}










 Let G be a graph with |V|=n.





 Suppose G is connected. Find a lower bound on |E|. Start by exploring examples for n=2,3,4,5. You do NOT have to prove your answer is correct.









 Suppose that G is disconnected. Find an upper bound on |E|. Start by exploring examples for n=2,3,4,5. You do NOT have to prove your answer is correct.

A graph G=(V,E) is bipartite if its vertex set can be partitioned into two sets A and B such that the only edges in G run between these two sets. Equivalently: we can color the vertices of a bipartite graph with two colors, red and black, so that adjacent vertices receive different colors.


The complete bipartite graph K_{n,m} is an example of a bipartite graph. Here are some more examples of bipartite graphs.






\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.25] %mathbook width=80%


\draw[thick] (0,0) -- (-1,1);
\draw[thick] (0,0) -- (0,1);
\draw[thick] (0,0) -- (2,1);

\draw[thick] (1,0) -- (2,1);
\draw[thick] (1,0) -- (1,1);
\draw[thick] (1,0) -- (0,1);


\draw[thick, fill=red] (0,0) circle (3pt);
\draw[thick, fill=red] (1,0) circle (3pt);

\draw[fill] (-1,1) circle (3pt);
\draw[fill] (0,1) circle (3pt);
\draw[fill] (1,1) circle (3pt);
\draw[fill] (2,1) circle (3pt);


\begin{scope}[shift={(4,0)}]

\draw[thick] (0,0) -- (0,.5) -- (.5,.5) -- (.5,0) -- cycle;
\draw[thick] (1,1) -- (1,-.5) -- (-.5,-.5) -- (-.5,1) -- cycle;

\draw[thick] (0,0) -- (-.5,-.5);
\draw[thick] (0,.5) -- (-.5,1);
\draw[thick] (.5,0) -- (1,-.5);
\draw[thick] (.5,.5) -- (1,1);

\draw[thick, fill=red] (0,0) circle (3pt);
\draw[thick,fill] (0,.5) circle (3pt);
\draw[thick, fill=red] (.5,.5) circle (3pt);
\draw[thick, fill] (.5,0) circle (3pt);

\draw[thick, fill] (-.5,-.5) circle (3pt);
\draw[thick, fill=red] (-.5,1) circle (3pt);
\draw[thick, fill] (1,1) circle (3pt);
\draw[thick, fill=red] (1,-.5) circle (3pt);



\end{scope}


\begin{scope}[shift={(8,0)}]

\draw[thick] (0,0) -- (1,0);
\draw[thick] (0,0) -- (-1,0);
\draw[thick] (0,0) -- (-1,.66);
\draw[thick] (0,0) -- (-1,-.66);
\draw[thick] (1,.66) -- (1,-.66);
\draw[thick] (1,0) -- (2, .33);
\draw[thick] (1,0) -- (2, -.33);
\draw[thick] (2, .33) -- (3,.66);
\draw[thick] (2, -.33) -- (3,0);
\draw[thick] (2, -.33) -- (3,-.66);

\draw[thick, fill=red] (0,0) circle (3pt);
\draw[thick,fill] (1,0) circle (3pt);
\draw[thick,fill] (-1,.66) circle (3pt);
\draw[thick,fill] (-1,0) circle (3pt);
\draw[thick,fill] (-1,-.66) circle (3pt);


\draw[thick, fill=red] (1,.66) circle (3pt);
\draw[thick, fill=red] (1,-.66) circle (3pt);

\draw[thick,fill=red] (2,.33) circle (3pt);
\draw[thick,fill=red] (2,-.33) circle (3pt);

\draw[thick, fill] (3,.66) circle (3pt);

\draw[thick, fill] (3,0) circle (3pt);
\draw[thick, fill] (3,-.66) circle (3pt);

\end{scope}

\end{tikzpicture}











